.TH TREE(1),User Commands,TREE(1)

.SH NAME
tree - list contents of directories in a tree-like format

.SH SYNOPSIS
tree [directory]

.SH DESCRIPTION
tree prints a recursive, indented listing of directory contents. If no directory is given, the current working directory is used.

Each entry is printed on its own line, prefixed with |---- and indented according to its depth in the tree. Trailing '/' (directory) and '*' (executable) markers emitted by ls -F are stripped before display.

tree is implemented by piping the output of ls -F and recursively invoking itself on each subdirectory. Because entries are streamed as they are read, files in a directory are printed before the contents of its subdirectories, rather than interleaved.

.SH LIMITS
Recursion depth is capped at 6. At most 8 subdirectories per level are followed; additional subdirectories at the same level are listed but not descended into. There is no limit on the number of files displayed per directory.

.SH EXAMPLES
List the current directory:

$ tree

List a specific directory:

$ tree /bin

.SH EXIT STATUS
tree exits 0 on success.

.SH SEE ALSO
ls(1)
